Introduction¶

No-show Dataset Description¶

This report describes the medical appointment of patients who showed up for their appointment and those that were absent. Different characteristics of the patients who went for appointment were also reported. Those characteristics includes the patients's identification number (ID), the patient's appointment ID number, the gender of the patients whether they are male or female, the scheduled day given to the patient, the appointment day to see the medical personel and the neighbourhood of the patient. Moreso, the age of the patients, the number of patients who enrolled in the Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Famlia", hencing receiving scholarship and those who did not, the number of patients with various health challenges such as hypertension, diabetes, being handicapped and the number of alcoholic patients were all represented in the report. Finally, the number of patients who received SMS,those that showed up for the appointment and those that did not show up for appointment were all represented in the report.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

Furthermore, the various characteristics enumerated above were explored to know the relationship that exist between them. This further provide insights into the patient's personality and to highlight the factors that would make the patients show up for medical appointment. To achieve these, several questions were asked and some of the questions include:

  1. What factors determine whether a patient will show up for appointment or not?
  2. Does receiving SMS and being enrolled in the scholarship program influence more patients to show up for appointment?
  3. Does being handicapped and having little health challenges hinder patients from showing up on the appointment day?
  4. What is the age bracket of patients who showed up the most for appointment? These questions and many more will be addressed in the data analysis and conclusion sections.

Research Question 5: What factors are important to know in order to predict if a patient will show up on their appointment day or not?¶

1. First, let's look at two factors at a time to predict if the patient will show up or not.
2. To achieve this, one of the factors will be an independent variable ('no_show' = 1 column) and the other will be a dependent variable.
3. Secondly, let's create a function that calls for other factors for patients that showed up and those absent.
4. Also remember that the ('no_show' = 1) column has been turned to a dataframe.

In [44]:
def beam(var):
    
    showed_up[var].value_counts().plot(kind="bar",color='red', fontsize=12, label = 'show up', figsize=(6,6))
    absent[var].value_counts().plot(kind="bar",color='blue', fontsize=12, label = 'absent', figsize=(6,6))
    plt.xlabel(var, fontsize = 12)
    plt.ylabel('Number of Patients',fontsize = 12)
    plt.title(f'{var} distribution of patients that showed up for medical appointment VS those absent')
    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1), loc='upper right', borderaxespad=0.4);
In [45]:
beam('diabetes')

  3. In addition, MORE female patients showed up for the appointmeny than the male patients that showed up for the appointment.
  4. Again, MORE female patients were absent than the male patients absent for the appointment.
  5. MORE female patients showed up than the female patients absent.
  6. MORE male patients showed up than the male patients absent.

# Also, the "beam" function created above would not give a clear description to know if all patients showed up on the scheduled day unless it is represented in a line graph
# So let us create another function called 'fin'

def fin(var):
    
    showed_up[var].value_counts().plot(kind='line', color='red', label= 'show up', figsize=(8,8),);
    absent[var].value_counts().plot(kind='line', color='blue', label= 'absent', figsize=(8,8));
    plt.xlabel(var, fontsize = 12)
    plt.ylabel('Number of Patients',fontsize = 12)
    plt.title(f'{var} for showed up patients')
    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1), loc='upper right', borderaxespad=0.4);

In [76]:
#Since the values are the same all through, the subsequent codes will be grouped against no_show column
#So, let's create a function to loop through patients who showed with with two other variables.

def hit_plot(var1,var2):
    showed_up.groupby([var1,var2]).count()["no_show"].plot(kind="bar",color='red',alpha=.5, fontsize=12, label = 'show up', figsize=(6,6))
    absent.groupby([var1,var2]).count()["no_show"].plot(kind="bar",color='blue',alpha=.5, fontsize=12, label = 'absent', figsize=(6,6))
    plt.xlabel(f"{var1} and {var2}", fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel('Number of Patients',fontsize = 12)
    plt.title(f'{var1} and {var2} for showed up patients')
    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1), loc='upper right', borderaxespad=0.4);
In [77]:
hit_plot('sms_received', 'scholarship')

Result:

  1. From the graph above, the patients who showed up for appointment, who DO NOT receive SMS and ARE NOT enrolled for scholarship are more than the patients that showed up for appointment but received these benefits (scholarship and SMS). Therefore, patients who receive SMS and scholarship and showed up for appointment are LESS than those who do not receive the two.

def jack_pot(var):
    showed_up.groupby([var]).age.mean().plot(kind='bar', color='r',label= "show up", fontsize=12)
    absent.groupby([var]).age.mean().plot(kind='bar', color='b', label= "absent", fontsize=12)
    plt.xlabel(var, fontsize = 12)
    plt.ylabel('Average Age of Patients',fontsize = 12)
    plt.title(f'Age and {var} as a factor for showed up patients')
    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1), loc='upper right', borderaxespad=0.4);

Conclusions¶

SUMMARY¶

The medical appointment dataset of patients that showed up for appointment were investigated. The summary of the investigation showed that:

  1. Most patients that SHOWED UP for appointment DID NOT enroll for the scholarship program. This implies that irrespective of the scholarship benefit, patients still showed up whether they get the benefit or not.
  2. Most patients that SHOWED UP for appointment do not have diabetes, not hypertensive, not handicapped and not given to alcoholism. This indicates that patients who are healthy (healthy in this case means patients with no diabetes, not hypertensive, not given to alcohol, not handicapped) showed up more for appointment than those that are not.
  3. One could possibly suggest that the patients with health challenges (having diabetes, being hypertensive, alcoholic and handicapped) could not show up for appointment because of their condition. However, the results showed that among those with these health challenges, more patients still showed up while lower fraction were absent.
  4. Sending SMS to patients to show up for appointment does not influence the patients to show up for appointment. This means that patients who DID NOT receive SMS showed up more than those patients that received SMS.
  5. Patients SHOWED UP more when the deadline for appointment period is near. More so, they tend to show up more for appointment between the month of April and June 2016. This could be because the weather is shifting from the cold winter season to spring and summer, hence more conducive to go out at such season than the cold season
  6. Female gender showed up more for appointment than the male gender.
  7. The age bracket of patients who showed up more for appointment is between 0-37 years old implying that young patients tend to show up more than the older patients
  8. The factors that might influence whether a patient will show up on the appointment day or not are gender, age and the period slated for the appointment.

Limitation¶

  1. Enough features that could help predict whether the patients will show up for appointment or not were not given.

Additional Research¶

  1. It would be helpful to research on the geographical region of the neighborhood so as to determine if distance to the appointment center plays a significant role to patients showing up for appointment or not.
  2. Since most patients that showed up on the scheduled day did not show up on the appointment day, it will be helpful to research on the conduct/behavioral attitude of the hospital workers towards the patients that showed up on the scheduled day.
  3. It will be of advantage to investigate the effect of weather season on patient showing up on the appointment day.
